<subSubSection id="A279E9C243A2F4AD0D1E7118E115DF84" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type locality">
<paragraph id="333AA20975D9E209953C11C32EA11253" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FC447A4983DDD565B874172ECC189095" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Georgia, Mtskheta-Mtianeti Region, Kistinka (= Khde, Khdistkhali) River (along the Georgian Military Road, 1300 m a.s.l.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="069C9F4803B6FD97925A8E1ED7850432" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E3DCE12572535EB1307FC935427C9696" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4B53469D14E29763B36350EF887F28" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Georgia, south-western Russia, Turkey, Cyprus Island, northern Iraq, northern Iran (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8979ED1AD86B74D6B0667738AAC7ACDE" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Geographical (left) and vertical (right) distribution of Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471934" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B9F3079573C51B7FF94362EA965F87D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="C063CDED08D9F5C4ADF1EE213200A66A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E1C85A397DB8C844DB461F908E334019" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Larvae inhabit small streams and rivers at low to high altitude. Altitudinal range of sampling sites 280-2100 m a.s.l. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BC6A6BCA7557B05E68387A6A6BCDF680" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Geographical (left) and vertical (right) distribution of Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471934" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</figureCitation>
). Most frequently found above 1000 m a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC45E209E1D741E1E4DE78756272D025" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="main morphological diagnostics of larvae">
<paragraph id="67ABABA4604213E9CEE2D2FE68AEDE9A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Main morphological diagnostics of larvae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C02E1C4D5E9C20DDE21C40E5A1B4988C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(i) abdominal sterna II-VI with a pair of triangular spots; nerve ganglia often with spots (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E995C5856B14C480EADCC14F13593EB5" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, - G middle leg in dorsal view H, - I abdominal terga (arrows point on dorso-posteriorly extended lateral stripes) J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471935" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">13B, J</figureCitation>
); (ii) abdominal terga V-VII with lateral stripes extended dorso-posteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4734D172720E0A107D4B367E81F4E34E" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, - G middle leg in dorsal view H, - I abdominal terga (arrows point on dorso-posteriorly extended lateral stripes) J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471935" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">13H, I</figureCitation>
, arrows); (iii) tergum X with postero-lateral projections (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="382C11D302CB81A431A33BA4E64444E5" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K, L abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrows point on postero-lateral projection) M, sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471936" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14K, L</figureCitation>
, arrows); (iv) femora with rounded medial hypodermal spot (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5B7050910CEEC1578924EFB7AF862E9E" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, - G middle leg in dorsal view H, - I abdominal terga (arrows point on dorso-posteriorly extended lateral stripes) J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471935" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">13F, G</figureCitation>
); (v) setae on abdominal terga hair-like (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CC9CF28AEB2D0BDE6C02E6904A48794A" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K, L abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrows point on postero-lateral projection) M, sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471936" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14E</figureCitation>
); (vi) denticles along posterior margin of tergum VII strongly sclerotized and dense (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DAF0A882F9D253A044B490DB32B919E3" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K, L abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrows point on postero-lateral projection) M, sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471936" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14E</figureCitation>
); (vii) gill plates VII (in natural position from ventral view) wide (Figs 
<figureCitation id="D406BD6A69F9F673195F32AB2F73E34F" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, - G middle leg in dorsal view H, - I abdominal terga (arrows point on dorso-posteriorly extended lateral stripes) J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471935" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">13K</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5C0A8C607C9E1B86A849EFB4300EC27D" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K, L abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrows point on postero-lateral projection) M, sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471936" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14H-J</figureCitation>
); (viii) gill plates III with developed projection (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7596CC17D2EE922F78888B76B0EF453F" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Epeorus (Caucasiron) nigripilosus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K, L abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrows point on postero-lateral projection) M, sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471936" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CB71A8890B676D8B04623AEC741E2D6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="06D9172D75C35E449F074C76D520AB37" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD116D0941B8F8DA7BA37A20FC1F9AC3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="475D014F2EFEAC3B47F2717EBAD6CA5D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="68AD92806F3C29A420C97BABEC0EDFED" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Taxonomy</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
This species was described based on larvae from Georgia (Kistinka River) (
<bibRefCitation id="FC91371D1CAF63F84349373AC4AAED77" author="Sinitshenkova, ND" journalOrPublisher="Entomological Review" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="85 - 92" refId="B43" refString="Sinitshenkova, ND, 1976. Mayflies of the genus Iron Eaton (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae) in the fauna of the Caucasus. Entomological Review 55: 85 - 92" title="Mayflies of the genus Iron Eaton (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae) in the fauna of the Caucasus." volume="55" year="1976">Sinitshenkova 1976</bibRefCitation>
). Type series is deposited in IZ (
<bibRefCitation id="8B44DE7862C91A14C1AB051FA37D25CF" author="Kluge, NJ" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, St. Petersburg" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B29" refString="Kluge, NJ, 1995. A catalogue of the type-specimens in the collection of the Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, Insecta: Ephemeroptera. Zoological Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, St. Petersburg" title="A catalogue of the type-specimens in the collection of the Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, Insecta: Ephemeroptera." year="1995">Kluge 1995</bibRefCitation>
). Male imago was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="86E6C92A380C14D6AED520DC937E6BD1" author="Braasch, D" journalOrPublisher="Reichenbachia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="283 - 294" refId="B7" refString="Braasch, D, 1979. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gattung Iron Eaton im Kaukasus (UdSSR) (III) (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae). Reichenbachia 17: 283 - 294" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gattung Iron Eaton im Kaukasus (UdSSR) (III) (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae)." volume="17" year="1979">Braasch (1979)</bibRefCitation>
based on the material from the western Caucasus (Teberda River) associated with larvae according to similar coloration of abdominal terga and sterna. Female imago not described. Male genitalia similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A632EC3352D4DECDA8345B77E205A7B7" genus="E." lsidName="E. (C.) caucasicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="caucasicus" subGenus="C.">E. (C.) caucasicus</taxonomicName>
according to 
<bibRefCitation id="B3B2227090A81036A2797EDBE30F504D" author="Braasch, D" journalOrPublisher="Reichenbachia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="283 - 294" refId="B7" refString="Braasch, D, 1979. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gattung Iron Eaton im Kaukasus (UdSSR) (III) (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae). Reichenbachia 17: 283 - 294" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gattung Iron Eaton im Kaukasus (UdSSR) (III) (Ephemeroptera, Heptageniidae)." volume="17" year="1979">Braasch (1979)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
